[ASSISTANT] To achieve playback of a video in a specific quality, such as 144p, you can implement a custom track selection logic in the `CustomTrackSelector` class. The key is to filter out tracks that do not meet your desired quality criteria. Below is a basic example that prioritizes 144p video tracks:

```java
import android.content.Context;
import com.google.android.exoplayer2.DefaultRenderersFactory;
import com.google.android.exoplayer2.ExoPlayer;
import com.google.android.exoplayer2.RendererCapabilities;
import com.google.android.exoplayer2.RendererCapabilities.AdaptiveSupport;
import com.google.android.exoplayer2.RendererCapabilities.FormatSupport;
import com.google.android.exoplayer2.RendererCapabilities.TrackType;
import com.google.android.exoplayer2.RendererConfiguration;
import com.google.android.exoplayer2.SimpleExoPlayer;
import com.google.android.exoplayer2.trackselection.DefaultTrackSelector;
import com.google.android.exoplayer2.trackselection.TrackGroupArray;
import com.google.android.exoplayer2.trackselection.TrackSelection;
import com.google.android.exoplayer2.upstream.DefaultBandwidthMeter;

public class CustomTrackSelectionExample {

    private ExoPlayer exoPlayer;

    // Initialize ExoPlayer with a custom TrackSelector
    private void initializePlayer() {
        DefaultRenderersFactory renderersFactory = new DefaultRenderersFactory(context);
        TrackSelector trackSelector = new CustomTrackSelector(context);
        exoPlayer = new ExoPlayer.Builder(context, renderersFactory)
                .setTrackSelector(trackSelector)
                .build();
    }

    // Custom TrackSelector implementation
    private static class CustomTrackSelector extends DefaultTrackSelector {

        public CustomTrackSelector(Context context) {
            super(context);
        }

        @Override
        protected TrackSelection[] selectTracks(RendererCapabilities[] rendererCapabilities,
                                               TrackGroupArray[] rendererTrackGroupArrays,
                                               int[][][] rendererFormatSupports) {
            // Filter tracks to prioritize 144p video
            for (int i = 0; i < rendererCapabilities.length; i++) {
                if (rendererCapabilities[i].getTrackType() == TrackType.VIDEO) {
                    int formatCount = rendererTrackGroupArrays[i].length;

                    for (int j = 0; j < formatCount; j++) {
                        int trackFormatSupport = rendererFormatSupports[i][j][FORMAT_SUPPORT_MASK];

                        if (trackFormatSupport == FormatSupport.YES
                                && rendererCapabilities[i].getAdaptiveSupport() == AdaptiveSupport.NOT_ADAPTIVE) {
                            // Non-adaptive track, check if it is 144p
                            int height = rendererTrackGroupArrays[i].get(j).getFormat(0).height;
                            if (height == 144) {
                                // Select the track for 144p video
                                return new TrackSelection[]{new FixedTrackSelection(rendererTrackGroupArrays[i], j)};
                            }
                        }
                    }
                }
            }

            // If no suitable track is found, use the default selection logic
            return super.selectTracks(rendererCapabilities, rendererTrackGroupArrays, rendererFormatSupports);
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, the `CustomTrackSelector` iterates through the available video tracks and selects the one with a height of 144 pixels. The `FixedTrackSelection` class is a custom implementation to select a specific track. This example assumes that non-adaptive video tracks are available and that the desired 144p track is present in the available tracks.

Keep in mind that the actual implementation might vary based on the specifics of the media you're playing and the ExoPlayer version you're using. Adjustments may be needed based on your specific use case and the details of the media content.

